@Becca 
I think you’re right. 

You put me in mind of a snort-chuckle funny tale my brother used to tell, about getting a flat fixed on his car down south. The punchline was: “Oh… y’all mean a TAAAAAHR!”

@N 

Your comment is like saying “It seems like almost every Broadway show has singing in it. It’s annoying.”

However, if you don’t like themes, the New Yorker puzzles usually don’t have them.

@LRM 

So....this was harder for you than for many of us...BUT you solved it anyway.  
Maybe congratulate yourself rather than rail at the puzzle?  You deserve to feel proud of achieving the solve.

@Mean Old Lady and @Steve L.

My assumption is that it was for April Fools Day.  

I thought it was a fun change.  Usually, I can figure out what all of the categories are, but today, I had no idea what tied the blue together, so they were just leftovers.  Definitely outside of my cultural education as well.

@Esmerelda 

...Or maybe malapropisms?

All I know is, I had the same thought with the same song and will be singing it all day.

@Seattlite

Thank you!  I always assumed that the EMU thing was some inside joke referring to the frequency of that answer in many puzzles. Now I don’t feel left out : )

I loved the puzzle - thank you all for breaking the Monday rules for a day. In general I don’t like April Fools joke but this is the best kind, I didn’t see it coming, big smile when I did and no harm done.

@Nina Dina 
Which ones weren’t real? BEEB? They just mean slang for BBC, right? So not too strange…

What ones were bothering you?

@Hungry Piggie I came here to comment on this also! 
This isn't 1950!
I solved most of the puzzle except for this section because I had no idea that Homo Sapiens would not include me. At a time when women's rights are being eroded -- just today Florida decided women can't have an abortion in the first trimester -- I would at least expect the NYT Crossword to see me as a human. Alas.

